title: Escort Passport Max 2 Radar Mount for Tesla Model S

description.text:
This is a window mount for the Escort Passport Max 2 for a Tesla Model S (all years).

As many know, the Tesla Model S windshield is coated with a radar reflecting surface, making radar detectors less sensitive or completely useless. There is, however, a small patch of uncoated area just to the left of the mirror/camera, right behind the rear view mirror. However, due to the location, it's almost impossible to mount the Passport Max with the sticky cup and get a view through that area.

This mount will correct that problem and give the radar detector a much wider field of view through the tiny opening. It has the added bonus of putting the detector out of the way and will no longer block the visor when lowered.

It will also prevent the radar detector from falling down all the time due to the sticky cup coming off (especially in high heat environment).

To use this, you will need to disassemble your Sticky Cup. You'll need the magnetic arm, the screw, washer and tightening cap. See the pictures... but it is pretty self explanitory.

Remove the tightening cap, pull out the screw, remove the magnetic arm.

Install the arm in the mount, slide the screw through the holes (mind the square side. Tightening cap goes on the right, with the cutout), put the tightening cap on and cinch it down a bit. If you are using the supported version, it doesn't need to be very tight, as the plastic will do the supporting, not the friction of the screw.

The unsupported version will require a lot of force, so I would consider possibly printing it out with a higher infill than 20%. But you can use the unsupported version on any windshield, really, since you can angle the radar detector in almost any fashion. With the supported version, it is designed specifically with the angle of the Tesla Model S windshield in mind - so the radar detector is level.

The supported version requires supports to print, unless you have a fantastic bridging setup. The unsupported version does not require any supports.

--EXTREME CAUTION PREAMBLE--
It is very difficult to fit this batterys into the box and wire them up. Open contacts will be very close when assembling. Short circuits can occure. Batterys can catch fire or explode! Please be very carefull while assembling and use some tape for isolating unessesary contacts!
Do not directly measure the length or your batterys with a measuring stick! Metal measuring sticks can short circuit the contacts!!

This is a housing to fit in 4 18650 lithium batterys in serial (4S1P). It has exits, spaces and canals to wire up everything internally. This model is designed for a total length of 131mm (2 batterys), check your battery length!! The length and space can vary depending on the manufacturer (and stuff life flat tops or soldering flags). You maybe need to resize the model for a perfect fit.

There are 2 versions provided, one for screws and one for adhesive. For the screw version you need 4 times M2x20 + 4 times M2 nuts. I did not tested the adhesive version myself.

RL pictures show the prototype.

-Could also be used for 2S2P

title: Prusa i3 Titan Aero carriage & fan duct

description.text:
This is a carriage for a i3-based printer to hold an E3D Titan Aero extruder, and an optional 18mm/12mm inductive sensor and 50mm radial fan.

It is made to work optimally with the following components:

  • E3D Titan Aero extruder https://goo.gl/KxWhXG
  • 13Nm pancake stepper motor (larger one works but will prevent mounting a fan) https://goo.gl/bPWMrz
  • 5015 blower fan (optional) e.g. https://goo.gl/VYYVch
  • LJ18A 18mm inductive bed sensor (optional) e.g. https://goo.gl/MbEny7 - I also included a mount for a 12mm sensor e.g. https://goo.gl/TYrgW8
  • Works both with the old tension screw and newer thumb screw on the updated Titan extruder
  • Intended to be used with toolson's X endstop holder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1037870

This is a modular design, so if you need an attachment for a particular sensor, it might be possible to modify/create a sensor holder to your needs.

This is a compact design, with low clearances. Make sure you use insulation on the hotend block to protect the carriage and keep temperatures up when blowing with the layer fan. More info about the one I'm using here: http://e3d-online.com/Socks-Launch

Change log
2017-05-08: Replaced the fan vent to a new design that reaches around to both sides, the previous one did not work as well as I had hoped. If you have the old one, I recommend printing version 2 instead.

• First, attach the inductive sensor holder to the bottom of the carriage. Use CA/super glue for best stability, or zip-ties if you don't have glue.
  • Attach the linear bearings using zip ties.
  • Attach the stepper motor and titan extruder & hotend
  • Attach the inductive sensor and screw it in place
  • Attach the fan duct by inserting it into its slot in the sensor holder
  • Attach the 5015 blower fan using two zip ties and make sure it slots into the fan duct. I had to trim my fan a little bit with a hobby knife on the plastic "seam" that sticks out.
  • The belts are attached by just creating a loop and inserting it into the carriage slots.

These files have been designed to be printed without supports.

Make sure you print in a heat resistant material (don't use PLA), I used ABS.

Print one carriage. If you don't have a fan or inductive sensor, that is all you need.

If you have a 18mm inductive sensor:

  • Print a fan duct and the 18mm sensor holder.

If you have a 12mm inductive sensor:

  • Print a fan duct and the 12mm sensor holder.

If you don't have an inductive sensor but have a fan:

  • Print a fan duct and the fan holder without sensor mount.

Printing the fan duct:
Don't use supports inside the duct, as you'll have a really hard time getting the supports out. In the latest Slic3r version, there is a setting to only add supports that originate on the bed, which worked pretty well for me.

title: Tronxy/3DCStar P802 Z-Axis Threaded-Rod Bearing Holder/Stabilizer

description.text:
This is a great, easy upgrade to stabilize the Z-Axis threaded rod. Simply press-fit a 8x22x7 bearing into the holder, glue (solvent is best if printed in ABS) on the nub, and fit the holder into the existing threaded-rod hole in the acrylic chassis.

The holder is designed to be a snug interference-fit, so simply heat the bearing to 70C (for PLA) and then press the bearing into the holder. Do not overheat or the holder will deform!

There is built-in compensation for FDM printing clearance of 0.8mm between the nub and the centering socket on the holder, to allow for +0.4mm of oversize on the nub, and +0.4mm undersize on the receiving socket.

Wrap one layer of Kapton tape around the threaded-rod to make it fit snugly into the bearing (i.e. you want to bearing inner race to rotate with the rod).

No drilling of the chassis or cutting of rods need to be done. The bearing holder is designed to have a low profile when installed, so simply loosen the set screws on the Z-coupler to accept the holder. Make sure to push up on the threaded rod to butt the holder up tight against the top acrylic frame plate before tightening the set screws.

UPDATE #1: A single-piece .STL and .GCODE have been added ... if you are comfortable with printing and removing supports. The .GCODE is pre-sliced with supports, and I recommend using this as it can be difficult to get the settings right for supports (that you can actually remove) -- just be sure to modify the three temperatures lines to suit your material.

UPDATE #2: The clearance for the bearing (as well as for the nub) has been reduced by 0.2mm to make it a more snug fit.

title: Spool Holder for small build plates

description.text:
I needed a spool holder for my Huxley 3D printer. It's build plate however is only 140x140 mm which is too small to print a decent spool holder. As I couldn't find a spool holder on Thingiverse that has been optimized for this small build plate, I created one myself with inspiration from 'Another Filament Spool Holder' (see remixed from), which is based on smaller parts.  
This design is printed in 7 parts, which snaps together into one solid spool holder. You can also break apart the spool holder in between prints and throw it inside a drawer to save some space.  
See the attached rendered image for an exploded version of the design to give you a good idea which parts goes where. In essence, all parts need to be printed twice, with the exception of the beam.

Print all parts twice except for the beam (choose either the plain version, or the one with support). All parts should snap together with some force applied. See attached image for an exploded view of the design.  
The force of the printhead might work as a lever at high Z and could therefore use something to brace. I didn't need it using blue tape which really sticks. But anyway I've included a .stl file for the beam with support in case you need it.

description.text:
This is my take on the Slim Wallet of Pentland designs. I wasn't totally happy with what he made so I changed it until I was! :)

The changes that I made:

  • The lock and the arm for the cards are now on opposite sides. This makes for a seamless one hand experience.
  • There is a stop in the hinge which makes it not turn further than about 60 degrees. This way you are always able to push the cards down.
  • There where some small inconsistencies in the thickness of the card arm which caused multiple cards to pop up on the same step. So changed that.
  • because this model required very tight tolerances I moved the lock pieces up so it is easier to move after printing.
  • I removed the hole on the bottom. I know this is used to crack the arm loose but I used a different method for that.

If you are a lefty you might want to mirror the model! :p

How do I print this?
The way this is easiest for you printer to print is to have the arm separate from the rest of the model on the build-plate.
After printing you can then insert the arm in the rest of the wallet. You might want to use a heatgun to soften the plastic a bit so it is easier to get it in.

This is a laboratory sample rotator designed so that can be used for tumbling as well as gentle mixing of samples in a variety of tube sizes by mixing them horizontally, vertically, or any position in between. Changing the mixing angle is fast and convenient and requires no tools. This device is has an on-board Arduino-based microcontroller incorporated so that adds the functionality of a laboratory sample shaker. These devices can be customized both mechanically and functionally as the user can simply select the operation mode on the switch or alter the code to perform custom experiments. The open source laboratory sample rotator mixer can be built by non-specialists for under US$30 and adding shaking functionality can be done for under $20 more. Thus, these open source devices are technically superior to the proprietary commercial equipment available on the market while saving over 90% of the costs.

For a complete BOM, the code, all design files, and stls and instructions see main source page and paper here:

title: Vertical X Idler with Belt Tensioner

description.text:
This is a replacement for the TEVO Tarantula X Idler with integrated belt tensioner.
Y Version

There are 2 versions of Case and Lid files. For stock size pulleys that came with Tarantula, print the 'Stock Idler' files. Other version uses wider pulleys if desired.

Belt animation: http://gph.is/2peM8qw

*NOTE - one of the idler pulleys shares an axle with a V-Wheel. Use a 50mm M4 screw here.

UPDATE 1: Adding versions with 8mm extra belt clearance for linear rails such as MGN12.

comments.text:
I think there's one flaw in this great design, the excentric nuts should be on the inside of the 20x20 extrusion.
Because the one with the pulley can't be set without the bolt rubbing to the inside of the 5mm hole. This hole should be 6mm through both parts but then the bolts wont have a snug fit with the 2 plastic halves anymore. Therefore changing the 7mm counter sinked holes to the other side of the extrusion would be a better solution.
Update: After drilling the hole in question to 6mm and adjusting the excentric nuts everything fits however, as I feared, the bolt is now oblique and the belt pulls to one side now. So my suggestion seems to have merit.

description.text:
Hey there!

In case you like space stuff, this might be a nice item to decorate your desk.

The rocket is spit into two pieces which are simply plugged together when finished. Therefore this print works completely without rafts or support. (However, the gap between the booster rockets is approximately 12mm wide at 150% and the printer creates a bridge here. Bigger scales resulting in a wider bridge may cause a failed print). It also allows the use of multiple colors. The color change within the pieces where made with prusa's colorprint function (using the M600 gcode) , which can be found on prusaprinters.org. The printer just stops, moves away from the object and waits for the filament to be changed manually to allow single-extruder-multi-color prints.

The "hinge" or "nose", whatever you want to call it, on the main fuel tank may need a little afterwork in order to get the gap between the shuttle's engines and the smoke as small as possible.

It was not entirely my idea, actually it was inspired by "Lift Off" made by "Xonor13". (thing:2187088) Since that one requires supports, that are not available for me and ProEngineer can not alter stl files, I decided to try making my own version from scratch. I am pretty happy with the result.

Dimensions when printed at 150%:

  • Height: 107.5mm
  • Width bottom: ~70mm
  • Width main fuel tank: 12mm
  • Booster diameter: 3.55mm
  • Shuttle width: 24mm
  • Booster/Shuttle Engine diameter: 2.8mm
  • Bridge gap between boosters: 12mm

The shuttle comes with enlarged first layer bases, otherwise the wings would be ripped off before they are connected to the engines and the main body. In the stl file this layer has a height of 0.1mm , so choose your first layer height appropriately, otherwise your slicer may leave them out. You probably have to add a brim in case the engines don't stick to your print bed properly, but mine worked fine.

Anyway, I hope you appreciate my work. Constructive criticism and advices are highly appreciated!
Happy printing!

title: Monoprice MP Select Mini 3D Printer Spool Holder

description.text:
Small changes to cantizzy's spool holder:

  1. Made slightly wider to allow for 1kg spools from Monoprice to be used
  2. Shortened a bit - I don't use any spools that needed this height ~2cm
  3. Improved the tolerances where the sides attach so they'll attach more easily (still stay securely connected)
  4. Added a clip that secures the base to the stock spool holder
  5. Improved the tightness and fit of the base to the stock spool holder - it is now very snug

To assemble:

  1. Slide the base on from the end - flat side toward the printer, it will be tight as passes the upturned end, but should slide on, slide it up the base a bit.
  2. Slide the clip onto the end of the base. Pointed side should be on top.
  3. Slide the base back under the clip until the point catches.
  4. Slide on sides so they are angled away from printer.
  5. Slide in axle (with spool) and turn to lock.

title: Anet A8 (Prusa) Y Axis Belt Clamp

description.text:
The original y-axis belt anchors broke so I designed better replacements. These are stronger, and have a ribbed slot for the belt ends to fit into, so will never slip.

It's a tiny part, but vital!

Please leave a comment if you like...

Edit: Improved y-axis tensioner: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2249773

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.06mm

Infill:

70%

Notes:

Print two, obviously!

I used PLA, and they came out perfectly first time. ABS will work just as well if you allow for shrinkage, you might need to experiment with scaling to get it right.

First, I glued the broken pieces back together so I could measure them with a digital caliper.

I started by sketching a rectangle on the XY plane, same size as the width and length of the original. I added sketch fillets to the corners, exactly half the width so I get nicely rounded ends. The centres of the fillets then are the exact centres for the screw holes, and I added circles at these points, slightly larger than the nominal screw diameter (4mm).

Then I extruded the sketch profile upwards to the height of the original.

Next, I sketched a row of 5 circles on the YZ plane, 1mm diameter, 2mm pitch, to make the profile for the belt. I joined the circles along their centres, extending the ends beyond the width of the clamp, and joining them with lines to form a section of the belt.

Then I extruded that sketch symmetrically, by 6mm, to cut groves in the clamp.

I finished by adding chamfers to all the outer edges -not necessary, and probably not even visible in the finished object, but, as they say, 'the devil is in the detail'. :)

title: Nut holder - Adjustable for any nut size / space

description.text:
This is a template which can be used to create a nut holder to hold any hexagonal or square nut. By changing the parameters in the file you can control the following:

  • diameter and height of the nut holder
  • whether the hole for the nut is in the center of the part to print in place or on the top of the part for post print fitting.
  • how many dents are placed around the outside edge of the nut holder.
  • how deep these dents are in the nut holder.
  • how much the top and bottom edges are chamfered.
  • diameter and height of the nut.
  • thread size.
  • tolerance for the nut / thread holes.

I may decide to adjust the design in future to offer a "knurled" style of finish but I can't currently visualise how I intend to accomplish this. Three STL files have been uploaded as examples of a few simple variations that can be made with this template file.

Update - 03/03/2018 - Improved preview of parts achieved by making sure that volumes used to cut the dents and holes overlap each other slightly and overlap the edge of the volume we are subtracting from. Thanks go to user gadgetmind for suggesting the change in the comments.

Update - 03/03/2018 - Replaced the tolerance values in the code with a tolerance variable and explanation to make it clearer what we're doing.
